### Here is the problematic code

```ts
emails: teamProcedure
    .input(
      z.object({
        page: z.number().optional(),
        status: z.enum(statuses).optional().nullable(),
        domain: z.number().optional(),
        search: z.string().optional().nullable(),
      })
    )
    .query(async ({ ctx, input }) => {
      const page = input.page || 1;
      const limit = DEFAULT_QUERY_LIMIT;
      const offset = (page - 1) * limit;

      const emails = await db.$queryRaw<Array<Email>>`
        SELECT 
          id, 
          "createdAt", 
          "latestStatus", 
          subject, 
          "to", 
          "scheduledAt"
        FROM "Email"
        WHERE "teamId" = ${ctx.team.id}
        ${input.status ? Prisma.sql`AND "latestStatus" = ${input.status}` : Prisma.sql``}
        ${input.domain ? Prisma.sql`AND "domainId" = ${input.domain}` : Prisma.sql``}
        ${
          input.search
            ? Prisma.sql`AND (
          "subject" ILIKE ${`%${input.search}%`} 
          OR EXISTS (
            SELECT 1 FROM unnest("to") AS email 
            WHERE email ILIKE ${`%${input.search}%`}
          )
        )`
            : Prisma.sql``
        }
        ORDER BY "createdAt" DESC
        LIMIT ${DEFAULT_QUERY_LIMIT}
        OFFSET ${offset}
      `;

      return { emails };
    }),
```

### Alternative 1 : Here is the alternative prisma code without the use of raw query, BUT

It works for all other cases except partial search inside of array. 
- E.g, Searching partial portions inside the `to` emails array. It has to be one of the complete value of array. 


```
["alice@example.com", "bob@example.com"]

- "alice@example.com" will return the data
- "example.com" will not return the data
```

```ts
const emails = await db.email.findMany({
        where: {
          teamId: ctx.team.id,
          // Filter by latestStatus if provided
          ...(input.status && { latestStatus: input.status }),
          // Filter by domain if provided
          ...(input.domain && { domainId: input.domain }),
          // Filter by search if provided
          ...(input.search && {
            OR: [
              // Subject ILIKE '%search%'
              { subject: { contains: input.search, mode: "insensitive" } },
              // For the "to" array, Prisma can only do exact matches out of the box:
              // e.g. { to: { has: input.search } }
              // This will not replicate partial substring array matches.
            ],
          }),
        },
        orderBy: {
          createdAt: "desc",
        },
        take: DEFAULT_QUERY_LIMIT,
        skip: offset,
        select: {
          id: true,
          createdAt: true,
          latestStatus: true,
          subject: true,
          to: true,
          scheduledAt: true,
        },
      });
```


### Alternative 2 : Maintain a text based searchable field in database

Store the array in two forms in database:

1. As the original array
2. As a string that concatenates all the email addresses (for search purposes)


```ts
model Email {
  id                 String   @id
  createdAt          DateTime
  to                 String[] // raw array for “to” addresses
  toSearchableString String   // text field for searching
  ...
}
```

```ts
await prisma.email.create({
  data: {
    to: ["alice@example.com", "bob@example.com"],
    toSearchableString: "alice@example.com,bob@example.com",
    ...
  }
});
```
Then search with

```ts
const emails = await prisma.email.findMany({
  where: {
    toSearchableString: {
      contains: input.search,
      mode: 'insensitive',
    },
    teamId: ctx.team.id,
  },
});
```

### Conclusion

Both approach has their own pros and cons.


### Replication Steps

1. Go to emails list page
2. Choose any one status from the top right dropdown
3. DB query fails and Prisma log shows error in the terminal
4. Request timeouts
5. Since DB query failed, we always get "No emails found"

